# 🚛✈️🚢🚂 AI-Powered Multi-Modal Carrier Selection Agent — Procurement Co-Pilot

---

## 1. Problem Understanding

Companies ship goods using **multiple transport modes** — road (FTL/LTL trucks), ocean (container vessels, bulk carriers), air (cargo aircraft, belly cargo), and rail (freight trains, intermodal containers). Each mode has its own ecosystem of carriers, pricing structures, performance characteristics, and risk profiles.

When selecting carriers, procurement teams must:

- Compare **carriers within each mode** (which trucking company for Mumbai–Delhi?)
- Compare **across modes** (should we ship Shanghai–Hamburg by ocean or rail via the New Silk Road?)
- Handle **intermodal/multimodal chains** (truck → port → vessel → port → rail → last-mile truck)
- Process bids in **wildly different formats** per mode — ocean quotes in $/TEU with BAF/THC surcharges, air quotes in $/kg with fuel surcharges, truck quotes in ₹/ton/km

### Why Multi-Modal Makes This 10x Harder

| Challenge | Single-Mode | Multi-Modal |
|---|---|---|
| **Carrier comparison** | Apples to apples | Apples to aircraft to container ships |
| **Pricing structures** | One format | $/TEU, $/kg, ₹/ton-km, $/wagon — all different |
| **Performance metrics** | Transit time, OTD | Varies by mode: dwell time (ocean), flight delays (air), wagon turnaround (rail) |
| **Risk dimensions** | Weather, road conditions | Port congestion, airspace closures, track availability, customs clearance |
| **Capacity units** | Trucks/trailers | TEUs, ULDs, wagons, trailer-on-flat-car — incompatible units |
| **Lead times** | Hours to days | Days (road) to weeks (ocean) |
| **Carbon accounting** | g CO₂/ton-km (road) | Varies 50x between air and rail for the same cargo |

### The Core Insight

The real problem isn't "pick the cheapest carrier." It's: **given a shipment's constraints (urgency, volume, value, fragility, carbon budget), which mode-carrier combination across the entire origin-to-destination chain delivers the best total outcome?**

No existing Excel-based process can answer this question at scale.

---

## 2. Proposed Solution Approach

### The "Four-Brain" Multi-Modal Architecture

We extend the multi-agent approach with a dedicated **Mode Selector** brain — critical because mode selection must happen _before_ carrier scoring:

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              MULTI-MODAL PROCUREMENT CO-PILOT                │
│                                                              │
│  ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌───────────────┐   │
│  │  Brain 0  │ │ Brain 1  │ │ Brain 2  │ │    Brain 3    │   │
│  │   MODE    │ │ ANALYST  │ │ PREDICTOR│ │  STRATEGIST   │   │
│  │ SELECTOR  │ │          │ │          │ │               │   │
│  │           │ │ Scoring &│ │ Risk &   │ │ Allocation &  │   │
│  │ Road/Rail/│ │ Ranking  │ │ Forecast │ │ Optimization  │   │
│  │ Ocean/Air │ │ per Mode │ │ per Mode │ │ Cross-Modal   │   │
│  └─────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ └──────┬────────┘   │
│        │            │            │               │            │
│        └────────┬───┴────────┬───┘               │            │
│                 │            │                   │            │
│          ┌──────▼────────────▼───────────────────▼──────┐     │
│          │            FEEDBACK LOOP                     │     │
│          │   (Continuous Learning per Mode & Route)     │     │
│          └──────────────────────────────────────────────┘     │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

| Brain | Role | Why It's Needed |
|---|---|---|
| **Mode Selector** | Recommends optimal transport mode(s) for each shipment | Mode decision fundamentally changes the carrier pool; must come first |
| **Analyst** | Scores carriers within the selected mode using mode-specific criteria | Each mode has different KPIs (dwell time vs transit time vs wagon turnaround) |
| **Predictor** | Forecasts delays, cost drift, and capacity risk per mode | Ocean delay drivers ≠ road delay drivers ≠ air delay drivers |
| **Strategist** | Optimizes carrier + mode allocation across the entire network | Balances cost, time, risk, and carbon across all options |

---

## 3. Mode-Specific Carrier Scoring Dimensions

### 3.1 Scoring Criteria by Transport Mode

Each mode has unique performance dimensions. A single scoring model **cannot** work across all modes — the AI must maintain **mode-specific scoring profiles**:

#### 🚛 Road (FTL / LTL / Parcel)
| Criterion | Metric | Why It Matters |
|---|---|---|
| On-Time Delivery | % shipments within window | Most direct reliability indicator |
| Cost per ton-km | ₹ or $/ton-km | Primary cost benchmark |
| Fleet Size & Coverage | # trucks, lane coverage map | Capacity assurance |
| Damage/Claims Rate | Claims per 1000 shipments | Cargo safety |
| GPS Tracking Capability | Real-time / milestones / none | Visibility for downstream planning |
| Driver Safety Score | Accidents per million km | Compliance & insurance risk |
| Tender Acceptance Rate | % loads accepted vs tendered | Actual commitment vs. paper commitment |

#### 🚢 Ocean Freight (FCL / LCL / Bulk)
| Criterion | Metric | Why It Matters |
|---|---|---|
| Schedule Reliability | % sailings on-time (± 1 day) | Ocean is notoriously unreliable — 65% avg OTD |
| Port-Pair Coverage | Direct vs. transshipment | Transshipments add 3–7 days and risk |
| Container Dwell Time | Avg hours at port before pickup | Hidden cost of slow operations |
| Demurrage/Detention Cost | Avg demurrage charges per TEU | Major hidden cost for shippers |
| Rate Stability | Bid variance over 12 months | Ocean rates can swing 300%+ |
| Equipment Availability | Container repositioning score | Can they actually provide empty containers? |
| Carrier Alliance Membership | Alliance network (2M, Ocean, THE) | Affects routing flexibility |
| Carbon Intensity | g CO₂ / TEU-km (IMO CII Rating) | Regulatory pressure via EU ETS, IMO 2030 |

#### ✈️ Air Freight (General / Express / Charter)
| Criterion | Metric | Why It Matters |
|---|---|---|
| Flight Frequency | Flights/week on route | Determines booking flexibility |
| Cut-Off Time Reliability | % shipments making the booked flight | Missed flights = 24-48h delays |
| ULD Utilization | Avg load factor offered | Affects pricing and availability |
| Dimensional Weight Accuracy | Variance in quoted vs actual DIM weight | Billing disputes |
| Customs Clearance Speed | Avg hours to clear | Critical for time-sensitive cargo |
| Temperature Control Capability | Active/passive/none | Pharma, perishables compliance |
| Security Screening | RA3 / KC certification | Regulatory requirement for air cargo |
| Rate per kg Bracket | $/kg by weight break (45kg, 100kg, 300kg, 500kg, 1000kg+) | Non-linear pricing structure |

#### 🚂 Rail Freight (Domestic / Cross-Border / Intermodal)
| Criterion | Metric | Why It Matters |
|---|---|---|
| Wagon Turnaround Time | Avg days per wagon cycle | Asset efficiency |
| Route Electrification % | % of route on electric traction | Cost and carbon advantage |
| Interchange Efficiency | Avg dwell at interchange points | Multi-operator routes have handoff delays |
| Yard Capacity Score | Avg waiting time at yards | Bottleneck indicator |
| Block Train Availability | Can provide full block trains? | 30-40% cheaper than wagon-load |
| Cross-Border Capability | # border crossings supported | Critical for routes like China–Europe |
| Track Access Priority | Position in priority queue | Determines actual transit time |
| Last-Mile Integration | Own trucking / partner / none | Seamless door-to-door vs. rail-head only |

### 3.2 Unified Scoring Framework

Despite mode-specific criteria, we need a **unified carrier comparison layer** for cross-modal decisions:

```
Universal Score = f(
    Mode-Normalized Cost,          ← $/ton-km equivalent
    Mode-Normalized Reliability,   ← P(on-time) regardless of mode
    Mode-Normalized Speed,         ← days origin-to-destination
    Mode-Normalized Risk,          ← P(disruption) × impact
    Mode-Normalized Carbon,        ← g CO₂ / ton-km
    Cargo Compatibility Score      ← can this mode handle this cargo type?
)
```

---

## 4. AI / Agent / Optimization Techniques

### 4.1 Mode Selection Engine (Brain 0)

**Technique: ML-Based Mode Choice Model (Random Forest + SHAP)**

Academic research (ArXiv, NREL) shows tree-based ensemble classifiers significantly outperform traditional Multinomial Logit for freight mode choice:

**Input features per shipment:**
- Shipment weight, volume, value, commodity type
- Origin-destination distance and geography
- Required delivery window (urgency)
- Temperature/handling requirements
- Carbon budget constraint
- Historical mode performance on this lane

**Output:** Probability distribution over modes (e.g., 60% ocean, 25% rail, 15% air) — not a single answer, because the Strategist brain may split a large order across modes.

**Why Random Forest over deep learning?** Interpretability via SHAP — procurement teams need to explain _why_ the system recommends ocean over air.

### 4.2 Carrier Scoring Engine (Brain 1)

**Technique: Hybrid AHP-TOPSIS with Mode-Specific Weight Profiles**

1. **AHP (Analytic Hierarchy Process)** — establishes criterion weights, but with **separate weight profiles per mode**. On-time-delivery weight for ocean (where 65% OTD is normal) is calibrated differently than for road (where 95% is expected).

2. **TOPSIS Ranking** — carriers ranked by distance to ideal/anti-ideal solution _within their mode group_.

3. **ML-Augmented Weight Adjustment** — XGBoost model trained on historical award outcomes adjusts AHP weights per lane cluster. A lane with high rate volatility (common in ocean) automatically upweights "rate stability."

4. **Cross-Modal Normalization** — for the Strategist to compare across modes, raw TOPSIS scores are min-max normalized per mode and then converted to a universal 0–100 scale.

### 4.3 Predictive Risk Engine (Brain 2)

Mode-specific prediction models because delay drivers differ fundamentally:

| Mode | Model | Key External Signals |
|---|---|---|
| **Road** | LightGBM (delay classifier) | Weather, road conditions, traffic, driver hours regulations |
| **Ocean** | LSTM (port congestion forecast) + Survival model (blank sailing risk) | AIS vessel data, port capacity utilization, Shanghai CCFI index |
| **Air** | Gradient Boosting (flight delay predictor) | Airport congestion, airline on-time stats, jet fuel index |
| **Rail** | XGBoost (transit time estimator) | Track maintenance schedules, yard capacity, cross-border dwell times |
| **All modes** | Prophet / NeuralProphet | Rate forecasting — predicts where each mode's pricing is heading |
| **All modes** | Isolation Forest | Anomaly detection — flags suspicious bids across all modes |

### 4.4 Cross-Modal Allocation Optimizer (Brain 3)

**Technique: Multi-Objective MILP with Mode-Carrier Decision Variables**

This is the most complex component — it simultaneously decides **which mode** and **which carrier within that mode** for each shipment:

```
Decision Variables:
  x[i,m,c] = volume of shipment i assigned to mode m, carrier c

Minimize:
  α · Σ(cost[i,m,c] · x[i,m,c])                    ← Total cost
+ β · Σ(risk[i,m,c] · x[i,m,c])                    ← Risk exposure  
+ γ · Σ(carbon[i,m,c] · x[i,m,c])                  ← Carbon footprint
+ δ · Σ(transit_time[i,m,c] · x[i,m,c])            ← Speed

Subject to:
  - Demand coverage: Σ x[i,m,c] ≥ demand[i]        ← Every shipment covered
  - Mode constraints: cargo_compatible[i,m] = true   ← Can this mode handle the cargo?
  - Carrier capacity: Σ x[i,m,c] ≤ cap[m,c]        ← Don't exceed carrier capacity
  - Min/max carrier share per lane                    ← Avoid over-dependency
  - Transit time windows: transit[i,m,c] ≤ deadline[i]  ← Delivery deadline
  - Carbon budget per corridor                        ← Sustainability targets
  - Modal shift targets (% rail/ocean vs road/air)    ← Strategic goals
  - Intermodal feasibility constraints                ← Valid multimodal chain exists
```

**Scenario simulation layer:** Monte Carlo simulation stress-tests allocations against:
- Port strikes (ocean capacity → 0 for affected ports)
- Airspace closures (re-route to ocean/rail)
- Fuel price spikes (modal cost rankings shift)
- Seasonal demand surges (carrier capacity drops)

### 4.5 Bid Normalization Engine (Multi-Format)

Each mode has entirely different bid structures:

| Mode | Typical Bid Format | Normalization Approach |
|---|---|---|
| **Road** | ₹/ton, ₹/km, ₹/trip, $/mile | Normalize to **$/ton-km** using shipment weight & distance |
| **Ocean** | $/TEU + BAF + THC + ISPS + ECA + LSS | Decompose into base + surcharges; normalize to **$/TEU all-in** |
| **Air** | $/kg with weight breaks + FSC + SCC + AWC | Interpolate rate for actual weight bracket; normalize to **$/kg all-in** |
| **Rail** | $/wagon, $/container, $/ton | Normalize to **$/ton-km** using wagon capacity & distance |

**Technical approach:**
1. **LLM-powered extraction** (Gemini/GPT-4) — parse bids from PDFs, emails, Excel in any format
2. **Mode-specific schema mapping** — map extracted fields to canonical mode schemas
3. **All-in cost calculator** — add all surcharges to compute total landed cost
4. **Cross-modal normalization** — convert to $/ton-km equivalent for cross-modal comparison

### 4.6 Continuous Learning & Feedback

**Technique: Contextual Bandit with Thompson Sampling + Mode-Stratified Learning**

- Separate bandit models per mode — learning a new ocean carrier's reliability shouldn't affect road carrier exploration
- **Reward signal** = composite of actual cost, actual transit time, actual damage rate post-award
- **Bayesian priors** for new carriers — start with mode-average performance, update with each shipment
- Automated **model retraining triggers**: retrain when prediction error exceeds threshold, or carrier behavior shifts (detected via drift monitoring)

