## 6. Model Explainability Layer

### Three Levels of Explanation (per every mode)

| Level | Audience | Example Output |
|---|---|---|
| **Executive** | VP Procurement | "Shifting 30% of Shanghai–Hamburg volume from air to China–Europe rail block train saves $420K/year with only 5 days additional transit" |
| **Analyst** | Procurement Manager | SHAP waterfall: "Ocean Carrier X scored lower due to 3 recent blank sailings on Asia–Europe; Carrier Y has 40% better schedule reliability despite 8% higher rate" |
| **Auditor** | Compliance / Legal | Full decision trace: shipment data → mode selection → carrier scoring → optimization output → final recommendation with all weights and thresholds |

### Contrastive Cross-Modal Explanations

> "For this 20-ton electronics shipment Shanghai → Munich:
> - **Air** (recommended for 30% of volume): 4 days, $18.50/kg, 0 risk flags — for time-critical units
> - **Rail** (recommended for 70% of volume): 18 days, $3.20/kg, low risk — for buffer stock
> - **Ocean** (not recommended): 35 days, $1.80/kg — delivery window too tight
>
> If the delivery deadline were extended by 14 days, the optimal split would shift to 100% ocean, saving $52K."

